arcana (0.20.3-1) unstable; urgency=medium

  * openai:tts service gains an `inline: true` option. When set, the
    audio is returned as a base64 string in the response
    (`audio_base64`) instead of being written to `output_path`. The
    caller decides whether the file lives on disk or comes back on the
    wire. Either `output_path` or `inline: true` must be provided;
    missing both is a validation error.
  * `output_path` is now optional in the schema (was required); the
    handler enforces the "one of" invariant since JSON Schema
    conditional-required isn't wired in arcana-core's checker.

 -- trans <transfire@gmail.com>  Sat, 11 Jul 2026 00:00:00 +0000

arcana (0.20.2-1) unstable; urgency=medium

  * Auto-unwrap stringified-JSON payloads at the server boundary.
    Some MCP clients (and hand-rolled HTTP callers) encode the payload
    as `"{\"text\":\"hi\"}"` instead of nesting it as an object. Left
    alone, schema-validated services (openai:tts, anthropic:chat, ...)
    couldn't find their fields at the top level and replied "missing
    required fields." envelope_from_json now detects looks-like-JSON
    strings and parses them back to real structures before delivery;
    a literal string payload like "hello" is left alone.
  * arcana_deliver MCP tool description tightened to say "pass a JSON
    OBJECT" so future callers don't fall into the same pit.

 -- trans <transfire@gmail.com>  Sun, 05 Jul 2026 12:00:00 +0000

arcana (0.20.1-1) unstable; urgency=medium

  * Bump arcana-core to 0.5.2 for the Service poison-pill fix. Prior
    to this, a service that received a payload failing schema
    validation *because it wasn't a Hash* crashed its consumer fiber
    and stopped consuming its mailbox — every subsequent delivery
    piled up unprocessed. This bit the anthropic:chat and openai:chat
    workers in a live deployment. Now the caller gets a proper
    Protocol.need response and the loop keeps consuming.

