    events.
  * MCP server now returns an `instructions` field in the initialize
    response — a one-time workflow briefing ("register first, then
    deliver/receive, use arcana_directory for discovery") that the
    client carries as standing context. Tool descriptions stay
    focused on per-tool behavior instead of repeatedly explaining
    the same setup.

 -- trans <transfire@gmail.com>  Sun, 24 May 2026 00:00:00 +0000

arcana (0.19.1-1) unstable; urgency=medium

  * Fix migration runner: it used crystal-pg's prepared exec which is
    one-statement-only, so any migration file with more than one SQL
    statement (e.g. the init_auth schema with its 4 tables + indexes)
    failed at apply time with "cannot insert multiple commands into
    a prepared statement". Now splits on `;` and runs each statement
    in the same transaction.
  * Fix migration directory resolution: previously preferred
    $CWD/db/migrations even when empty, which silently masked a
    real install. Now prefers /usr/share/arcana/db/migrations and
    only falls back to CWD when running from a source checkout
    (shard.yml present).
  * No schema changes. Existing 0.19.0 deployments with the manually
    applied init_auth schema will see `schema_migrations` filled in
    on next migrate (no-op for the table contents).

 -- trans <transfire@gmail.com>  Wed, 20 May 2026 00:00:00 +0000

arcana (0.19.0-1) unstable; urgency=medium

  * Server-side bearer-token auth (stage 2 of 3 for SaaS auth).
    Set ARCANA_AUTH_REQUIRED=1 to require a valid
    `Authorization: Bearer ak_...` header on every REST call and
    WebSocket upgrade. /health remains open for liveness probes.
    Requires ARCANA_DATABASE_URL — the server refuses to start with
    auth enabled and no identity store.
  * Auth is fully opt-in. With ARCANA_AUTH_REQUIRED unset, the bus
    behaves exactly as before — anonymous access, single-tenant
    localhost. No breaking change for existing deployments.
  * Failed auth attempts are recorded as `auth.failed` events
    (transport=rest|websocket) for audit.
  * arcana-mcp bridge now forwards ARCANA_API_KEY as a bearer token
    on every HTTP call, so MCP clients work against an
    auth-enforcing server.
  * Per-listing / per-org tenancy isolation intentionally deferred
    to stage 3.

